
A company wants to automate build and packaging of its **Employee Management application**.
# ğŸ—ï¸ Step 1 â€“ Create Sample Application

Create a folder:

```
employee-management-app
```

Create file **Main.java**

``

  public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello from Docker!");
    }
}

# ğŸ³ Step 2 â€“ Create Dockerfile

Create file **Dockerfile** (no extension)

```dockerfile
FROM eclipse-temurin:21-jdk

WORKDIR /app

COPY . .

RUN javac Main.java

CMD ["java", "Main"]
```

---

# ğŸš« Step 3 â€“ Create .dockerignore

Create file named **.dockerignore**

```
*.class
.git
.github
```

---

# ğŸŒ Step 4 â€“ Create GitHub Repository

1. Go to [https://github.com](https://github.com)
2. Click **New repository**
3. Name: employee-management-app
4. Public â†’ Create

---

# ğŸ“¤ Step 5 â€“ Push Code to GitHub

Open terminal in project folder:

```bash
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Employee management app"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/USERNAME/employee-management-app.git
git push -u origin main
```

---

# âš™ï¸ Step 6 â€“ Create GitHub Actions Pipeline

Create folders:

```
.github/workflows
```

Create file:

```
docker-build.yml
```

Paste:

```yaml
name: Build Employee App Docker Image

on:
  push:
    branches: [ "main" ]

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
    - name: Checkout code
      uses: actions/checkout@v3

    - name: Build Docker image
      run: docker build -t employee-app .

    - name: Show Docker images
      run: docker images
```

---

# ğŸ“¤ Step 7 â€“ Push Pipeline Files

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Add GitHub Actions pipeline"
git push
```

---

# âœ… Step 8 â€“ Verify Pipeline

1. Open repository
2. Click **Actions** tab
3. Open latest workflow
4. Ensure **green tick**

---



The Employee Management application source code was pushed to a GitHub repository. A Dockerfile was created to containerize the application. GitHub Actions was configured using a workflow file to automatically build the application and generate a Docker image on every push to the main branch. The pipeline execution was verified successfully from the GitHub Actions dashboard, demonstrating automated build and container creation.

